<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911204-0131</DOCNO><DOCID>911204-0131.</DOCID><HL>   Michaels Stores' November Sales</HL><DATE>12/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MIKE</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>SPECIALTY RETAILERS OF LIMITED PRODUCT LINES (OTS)ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   IRVING, Texas -- Michaels Stores Inc. said its Novembersales rose 35% to $52 million from $38.6 million a year ago.   Sales at stores open more than a year increased 32%, thecompany said.</LP><TEXT>   Jack E. Bush, president and chief operating officer of thearts and crafts retailer, said Michaels benefited from acircular that ran in newspapers during the month and aspecial promotion following Thanksgiving, in which customerscould use &quot;Turkey bucks&quot; coupons to get 35% to 50% off asingle item during early morning shopping hours. In addition,he said better control of inventories and bigger offerings ofholiday products helped sales.   The company previously said that it had been able togreatly increase its seasonal purchases this year because itsinventory controls left it with more cash. An increase infall and Halloween-related inventory boosted the company'ssame-store sales in September and October by 20% or more.   For the first 10 months of fiscal 1991, Michaels said itssales increased 19%, to $318.7 million from $267.3 million.Sales at stores open more than a year rose 12% for theperiod.</TEXT></DOC>